<DOC><DOCNO> AP890628-0223 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-89 0322EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-28 0846</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0886</SECOND><DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge said nearly 43,000 coalminers on wildcat strikes in nine states are violating U.S. laborlaw and ordered them not to engage in any strike-related activities.   U.S. District Judge Dennis Knapp said Tuesday the walkout byUnited Mine Workers members violated National Labor Relations Actguidelines against secondary boycotts. The walkout began June 12 insupport of 1,900 UMW members who have been on strike against ThePittston Coal Group since April 5.   Knapp issued a temporary injunction at the request of theNational Labor Relations Board.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Air Line Pilots Association has askedfederal mediators to intervene in talks with strikebound EasternAirlines, a request that could complicate the troubled carrier'splans to reorganize.   The union made the request Tuesday of the National MediationBoard even as it continued negotiations with Eastern in talksordered by the bankruptcy judge overseeing the airline, which filedfor court protection from its creditors after its Machinists unionstruck in March.   Mediation Board spokesman David Bushnell said he believed amediation request involving a company in bankruptcy proceedings wasunprecedented and could not say what it would mean for Eastern's bidto abrogate the pilots' contract.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Banking regulators have threatened to raisereserve requirements for major U.S. banks with loans to developingcountries unless there is progress soon on Treasury SecretaryNicholas Brady's plan for reducing Third World debt.   The plan calls for commercial banks to forgive large amounts oftheir loans to developing nations, but it has run into stiffopposition from the banks in an early test over loans to Mexico.   William Taylor, director of banking supervision and regulationfor the Federal Reserve, issued the warning Tuesday at a HouseBanking subcommittee hearing.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Communications Commission denied arequest to delay a new pricing scheme scheduled to go into effectJuly 1 for the nation's largest long-distance company, ATandamp;T.   Competitors had requested a delay in June, saying a price-capregulatory scheme for American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co. would hurtthem and the public.   But the FCC, in a decision reached Friday and made publicTuesday, said the companies failed to provide adequate reasons for astay and that the public would benefit from the new pricing.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A decision is near on whether to extend steelimport curbs with 29 countries, according to government and industryofficials.   The five-year curbs expire Sept. 30.   Lawmakers on both sides of the issue expected President Bush toissue a decision, possibly by the end of the week, that seeks toappease both sides in the steel import barrier dispute.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House has ignored a veto threat and passedlegislation to pay more than $900 million to farmers sufferinglosses from drought and other weather disasters.   The assistance legislation, approved Tuesday on a voice vote andsent to the Senate, is aimed primarily at winter wheat growers inKansas, Oklahoma, Texas, Nebraska and other states. It also wouldprovide payments to some livestock producers.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The junk bond market, already troubled by theprospect of an economic slowdown, could suffer a heavy blow ifCongress adopts legislation forcing savings and loans to sell theirholdings of the high-risk, high-yield securities, economists say.   Nevertheless, members of Congress upset about the wave ofcorporate takeovers and leveraged buyouts are determined to pushthrifts out of the lucrative, but speculative, investment.</TEXT><DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   European leaders have made a deal to takethe first steps toward economic and monetary union, but PrimeMinister Margaret Thatcher of Britain fended off moves for a singlecurrency and one central bank.   Leaders of the 12-nation European Economic Community on Tuesdayfell far short of embracing sweeping proposals that would lead totight economic integration of the trading bloc.   Mrs. Thatcher was pitted against French President FrancoisMitterrand and West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who wanted aquick monetary marriage.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   UAL Corp.'s stock jumped in response to a reportthat a group led by Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass had acquired upto 3 percent of the company, which owns United Airlines.   Bass spokeswoman Susan Hawkins declined Tuesday to comment on thereport in USA Today, and UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins said the companywould not comment on the stock activity.   In New York Stock Exchange trading Tuesday, UAL rose $6.75 to$146 a share.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   Stock prices rose Tuesday on the strength of declining interestrates and rising oil company shares. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials rose 14.99 to 2,526.37.   U.S. Treasury bond yields fell to two-year lows on sentiment thatthe economy is slowing and interest rates are declining.   The dollar drifted lower against all major currencies except theJapanese yen.   Wheat futures prices bounded to a six-week high on the ChicagoBoard of Trade. Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower whileoil and precious-metals futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>